<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
When you use another person&#8217;s ideas or words in your writing, include their name and any relevant 
page number(s), in parentheses, immediately following the cited material.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Smith and Brown 112&#45;13).
</blockquote>
<br>
Or include their names in your sentence, with the relevant page number(s) in parentheses.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith and Brown suggest that &#34;the default position is markedly affected&#34; (121).
</blockquote>
<br>
When the author is referred to more than once in the same paragraph only the page number is needed 
for subsequent citations, as long as the work cannot be confused with others cited.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Smith and Brown 112&#45;13). In addition&hellip; was a 
	common feature (121).
</blockquote>
